  "text": "The two proxies for financial development might already account for the liquidity effect measured by the float portfolio. In the next paragraph this interpretation is further underlined with regression results in a sample with EMU countries only. 28 The coefficient corresponding to EMU is the sum of the coefficients of W * j,t and of (W * j,t ) * EMU. 29 This stands in contrast to [CITATION_1] who show that the coefficient on W float j,t is larger than on W * j,t . However, they do not include any other proxies for financial market development in their regressions. (11) and (12) and the residual value of the market portfolio share, i.e., the difference between the market and the float portfolio share, W dif f j,t , enter the regression at the same time, both are separately insignificant but jointly significant (specification (13)). This changes once the proxy for equity market development in country j, logmcap j,t , is left out of the regression (specification (14)). In this case, only the float portfolio share is significant. This shows that for the EMU sub-sample the float portfolio share indeed seems to capture some liquidity effects of total equity shares traded at stock exchanges if these effects are not accounted for separately by equity market development, namely logmcap j,t .",
